segments.text: California, mama.
Le dije, pues, ven pronto.
Vas y recoges el trofeo y vienes pronto por mí.
Le dije, y yo me voy.
Pues, entonces, se vino luego, luego, él en el trofeo.
Era un trofeo grande, nuevo.
Entonces, se viene él pronto.
Y llegó a Blumenthal con su esposa, porque ya estaba casada.
So my brother was there with his wife and all his piscators.
I got there and he said, Mom, I came for you.
So I came.
Then my brother paid me what I had piscated, and then I came.
When I came, I picked up
como de 200 a 300 pesos la temporada que yo, aparte de ropa, aparte de comida y de todo, porque ganábamos muy buen dinero.
Todavía quedó mucho trabajo cuando yo me vine, pero yo me tenía que venir porque mi muchacho había ido por mí.
Nomás llegamos aquí con mi mamá a arreglar todo y a visitar
Mi hermano y mi mamá.
Entonces dijo, mi mamá te vas a ir.
Le dije sí.
Me fui, como siempre, con toda mi familia.
Hasta California.
Este muchacho no sabía que yo iba por él.
But your husband doesn't go to California?
No, he always stayed in these places.
In these places?
Yes, he never went to California.
He never went anywhere.
He always stayed here.
What kind of work did he have?
Oh, in labor.
He always worked at the ranch.
Yes.
He always liked to work at the ranch because, well, I don't know, I think he had a lot of education in Spanish.
How much?
Cuántos años de educación?
Pues yo no sé, porque él estudió no aquí en México.
En México.
Él estuvo en México.
Para muchos años.
No, not much.
I think it was the first one.
The primary school in Mexico.
The primary school.
Six years.
That's what I know.
And then, he learned so well to speak.
It seems that he had studied English.
He studied it, he read it, like Spanish, and like speaking Spanish, he spoke English and everything.
Well, I didn't correct him because I didn't know how to speak it.
But the people who heard him speak said, it seems that your sir studied English.
But no, he took it from the people, but he had a very good head.
He had a very good head to learn it, you see?
And he spoke it like... Well, no, but I say in the language.
He had an accent to speak it, whether it was Spanish or English.
You see?
Like this boy who is in Noste.
I tell you that he studied a little.
That boy...
He writes very well in Spanish and English, and he speaks it, and everything.
And he studied very little.
Well, I don't know your time.
I don't know your time.
How much time can you spend here?
Here?
It's 11, 11 and a half.
There's a lot of time left.
Well then, there in California there were many, many fields.
No, thank you.
There weren't many, there were many fields in those years that I was there in 55.
There were many places, many fields of many people from Mexico and everywhere.
Right?
No.
No?
Yeah.
Entonces, nosotros, ese muchacho estaba en ese campo.
Somebody went out to the clubs, folks club.
Estaba en ese campo cuando nosotros llegamos y aproximadamente sería como las cinco de la mañana cuando llegamos a ese lugar donde estaba ese hijo que está ahorita en California.
Then my boy, Pita, arrives.
And then he goes to Apea.
He knew all his places.
He goes to Apea to look for him.
He stops at the door.
You?
No, I'm kidding.
And then... You?
You here?
Yes.
His mother.
He got scared.
I said, son, get ready.
I'll be back soon for you.
He said, well, I'm leaving soon.
He got everything ready.
He went.
He got on the truck and passed me by, very happy.
And he went with us to the place where we were going.
In that place is Farport, California.
That's where my boys were raised, all of them.
I worked there.
very hard, me and my children.
We got there because a year before, a year ago it was, we got to that place, we met a contractor from that place who
There was a very large field, as if it were a town.
And that gentleman, very kind, he and his wife, and I think he had three children, because the other family was already separated.
Well, we got there, they gave us a little house because all the apartments were small.
And we were...
I don't know...
Seven, approximately.
We had to be in that little room.
So...
Pure water, anywhere.
There were roads, yes, but it was water.
Then it was winter time.
The boy, his son, had to go with my son, who was the one we went to pick up from that place, with the one who was in Washington, because he lived there.
So he said, well, you're going to have to go and leave Washington.
And I had to find someone to go with him.
So I went and told his father, he's going to go.
He gives permission to his son to go with my son to Washington to go and leave his sister.
Yes, he says, of course, go.
They go.
Después de que llegamos de Texas, otro día se fueron para el estado de Washington.
Ellos cuatro llegaron a Washington, dejaron a mi hijo, regresaron para atrás los dos.
Bien, de salud.
Allí nos establecimos.
Entonces ya tenía mi hijo, que era el responsable de aquel troque, y de mí.
in that place.
So...
I never...
I was able to solve all the problems I had in my life.
And I thank God that I didn't go to school, but school was my mind and my head.
Yes.
That was my school.
A school of experiences.
Yes, even though I was very young, I got married at 16 years old, but God gave me that thought to direct, give advice to my husband and give advice to my nine children.
and direct my person to me.
Well, at that time, when I returned to California, I was not hopeful about my husband.
I was not hopeful about my son.
I was only hopeful about my person.
Yo estaba esperando el porvenir de la vida mía.
Yo llevaba como a 300 pesos, como a 300 a 400 pesos.
Yo tenía para salvar
lo que atrás podía sobrevenir en mí.
Entonces, mi muchacho, este que está en California, ya no era aquel.
Ya era otro hombre.
¿Por qué?
Porque ya no había estado al lado mío.
See?
Because they respected me.
Because what I said, that's what I did.
Because that's how I imposed them.
So, yes, he...
Todos mis hijos se casaron, fueron al army, vinieron, han tomado ya de hombres, ya de que ellos salieron del lado mío, pero a mí no me han molestado.
A mí no han sido mis hijos desobedientes conmigo que diga, mis hijos me han dicho esto, mis hijos me han dado lo otro a mí.
My children have seen me all the time.
And I don't have to say that my children have treated me badly, no.
No, no.
Everything they can do to me, they do.
Everything I can say, they do.
They have never bothered me.
It doesn't make them arrogant, it doesn't bother me.
And I tell them, if you are going to drink, and you come to drink here to my house, don't come.
If you come healthy and well, come.
But don't drink.
That is the time of the married.
But when they are at home and they come to drink every now and then, they don't tell me anything.
Like this one who came from the service.
He was upset and everything, but you're going to sleep and you're going to do this now.
There's nothing here.
See?
Everyone's like that.
So I don't have anything to say about them.
It's just that they've all been good.
And they were nine brothers.
But those who were fighting, or those who were cursing each other, they were nothing.
They, the first was the girl, who is the oldest.
They all played with their four little brothers or their five little brothers.
You are there, we don't want you here, that you are with us.
You are there.
And she was sitting there, just looking at those who were playing.
But she didn't mess with them, because they didn't admit it.
And she didn't have any more girls to play with.
She played with what she had.
She bought her a doll, she played with that doll.
She played with little things, but what was she doing?
No, nothing like that.
They were very good boys because that's how they got used to it.
The little brothers didn't have to fight.
The little brothers didn't have to say this or that.
Are all your daughters married?
My daughters?
Only this one is left.
That's all.
She is not married.
She is not married, she is still here in the house.
How old is she?
I think she is 24 years old.
And thank God that God has left her until now to think well.
Well then, what did we do?
No, we had a truck of the year.
I think I had only one year of use of the truck.
Well, I could have saved my truck.
But sometimes
that companies see people who are humble and they take over the position to do that.
You see?
Is your husband still alive?
No.
He died.
In what year?
I was already here.
I was here for about a month.
So...
I told him, they sent a letter.
And he said, you know what?
We're going to go for this truck.
I told him.
I told my boy.
Yo había mandado porque el truco era de Washington y yo sé los reglamentos que hay.
Pero como yo nunca, yo puedo sacar un carro de este estado y lo puedo llevar para otro estado.
Pero yo aviso y yo mando mi dinero.
¿Ves?
Así no me molesta, no le hace que esto venga con un carro nuevo.
Entonces, este...
He said, well, the truck is not here.
He said, the truck is outside the state.
I said, they told me in the letter.
And since that truck was not in my name, it was in the name of the older boy,
So I had to talk to the older boy and I told my boy.
I had already sent the payment that was behind that truck.
But I didn't know how he had taken it.
So they say, here they come.
As soon as they sent me the letter, they sent whoever picked it up.
So I said to the boy, look, you're not going to sign any papers.
I said, why?
They shouldn't pick up that truck.
I said, why?
We were short of money.
We were short of 18 bucks.
They shouldn't have picked up the money, I said.
Why?
I already sent the money.
And how did they pick up the money?
And now they want to pick up the money.
So they shouldn't have picked up the money since they came to pick up the money.
And you're not going to sign anything.
And besides that, you shouldn't sign because it's the boy's.
The boy is the one who has to talk to him and he has to sign it.
What do you think they did?
They said, no, let's just go to the agency.
Let's go, he said, because they want him there.
I said, well, he's not the owner of the truck.
Well, they took him.
On the way, they made my boy sign the papers, telling him not to sign them.
They took him and put him in the agency.
Oh, how did he think I was so mortified?
Well, then I went to look for the boy.
Well, no, he says, well, the truck.
No, my boy came and said, Mom, the truck stayed at the agency.
Why did you leave the truck at the agency?
I didn't tell you that you didn't have to sign any papers.
He said, well, they made me sign and they told me so much.
He says, but I already told you.
Why did you do it?
That's why they took him where they were talking to me, so that he could sign on the way, to make him believe and he would sign.
In these days, where do your children live?
In these days, where do your children live?
There you go, Janie.
Yes, the food.
Well, do your children now live all here or in Washington and California?
I have my whole family irrigated.
Look, come and see them.
Close it and come and see them.
I have them all here.
Come and see them.
Let's go.
To see them, my boys, in portrait.
Oh, in portrait.
In portrait.
Just a moment.
But where do they live?
Look.
These now.
Now they are all irrigated.
They are all...
Near here?
No, they are in the States.
I have one in Philadelphia.
In Philadelphia?
She is married to a Canadian.
Oh, really?
Yes.
She had a lot of education, my girl who is in Philadelphia.
How old is she?
She studied to become a model.
She finished her school.
Yes, that's good.
And this other boy who is in California.
California.
He's the boy I'm talking about right now.
He's studying to become a minister.
From what?
Minister.
Minister?
Yes, right now he already has five children.
Ah, that's nice.
And he got rid of the Catholic religion.
Yes.
Because he...
me gustaba mucho tomar y pues yo siempre batallé con él ves pero ahora que yo me vine él se fue de donde se criaron ellos para san jose california porque nosotros allí
We have been living in Farport, California for many years.
And what is his name?
His name is Baristo, German.
And he is currently in San Jose, California.
And he is a minister of what?
He is studying, he is still not receiving.
Of what church?
Of what church is Baristo Pentecostal, Eugenie?
Yaini!
Yaini!
Well, it doesn't matter.
Well, I think it's...
It's protestant.
Yes, I think it's... No, how do you say it?
No...
I think it's the God of Jehovah.
Yes.
Yes.
Y este otro, ahorita él reside todo el tiempo y allá se crió en Washington.
En Washington.
Toda su familia.
Él es silvestre alemán.
Silvestre.
Silvestre alemán es el más chico de los cuatro gramos.
Ah, sí.
Y silvestre vive en Washington.
En Washington.
¿En qué pueblo?
En...
In Sunnyside.
Sunnyside, Washington.
Yes.
Good.
Yes.
And now he's in Idaho.
Another Idaho?
No, himself.
He himself comes to Idaho.
Ah, yes.
Yes.
Well, it's been a while since he left.
Right now he's in Nairajo because he came to see me.
He was here in Washington.
He was here in El Valle.
Yes.
He was there.
And a month ago he went over there.
And right now he's in Nairajo.
Ah, yes.
Yes.
But he lives there in Washington.
Yes.
Yes, he raised his family there.
He has five families.
And what kind of work did he have?
Well, he did work.
He is a truck driver.
Oh, yes.
Yes, he works right now in the trucks.
Yes.
He was, he spent his years as a potato loader.
Yes.
All the potatoes.
Now he doesn't drive a truck, he owns a truck and he works with his trucks.
And that's where his work has gone.
And this other boy that I'm telling you is studying, he works right now in the city.
de trabajos esos de... con una... tiene también un troque de dompe y él hace freeways en las casas.
Ah, sí.
¿Dónde vive él?
He is the one who lives in San Jose.
Oh, in San Jose.
Yes, well.
This is three.
That's right.
And right now I have in Austin, I have two children.
Two children?
Yes.
What is Graviel in German?
Graviel, the oldest.
Yes, the oldest is in Austin.
He, all his life, he liked to be a mechanic.
Yes.
Because when he went to the service, he wanted to study for that.
Yes.
But he didn't pass the tests of the applications for that.
Yes.
But he...
through his head.
He practiced and he practiced.
He has a gas station in Austin.
A gas station in his country?
Yes.
And he is a mechanic.
And he manages that gas station.
And his boy too.
His boys too, but now one of them got married.
Right now he only has one son and they all got married.
Well, he had two daughters and two sons.
Yes.
And the other son who lives in Austin is?
Right now, the youngest boy is Roel, German, who is the youngest.
He lives in Austin.
Yes.
But he, I'm not very practical to say where he works, but
He married, no one knew that he could marry a girl from a family that I have known for many years.
All my family, the first one was raised with that Basque family, right?
Now that we came from California,
He met with that girl and with that Vázquez family, who was from Robestán, and that's where that family grew up, but he went to Austin.

So this boy, as he was going all the time, because they recognize him as his father, who is the oldest boy, he always wanted to be there when we came, looking at his brother and helping him in the garage.
Ah, yes.
Yes, he always likes to come to work and there.
That is five and six.
Where does the boy or girl six live?
Well, it's this one.
This one that I'm telling you about.
This one that I'm telling you about, he got married and he thought about it very well because he has
He got married, he got married to a very good girl, and she has a very good job.
She works in the office of the telephone and insurance.
She fixed all of that.
He got married, he did his application, and then he left because he worked here in the pants factory.
The pants factory.
Since he left school, my boy worked there.
What was his name?
Roel Alemán is the one I'm talking about.
Roel Alemán.
And he lives here.
No, he lives in Austin.
In Austin.
In Austin.
He's the youngest of the greats.
Yes, yes, yes.
All right, yes.
So, he worked here, got married, and left work, and applied, and then he left.
So, he came in with his father-in-law to do all this work.
Yes.
Of carpentry and everything.
He...
He told his wife, let's both work together because those workshops are very big.
He did the application and he has a very good memory.
So he took, they gave him to study, he passed all the exams of that class of work.
Y ahorita tiene el muy buen trabajo y le dieron una máquina para que él estudiara mucho eso.
Ese trabajo que está haciendo él es de puro botón.
Puro botón.
Bueno.
And now he works at night.
And he learned all of that very soon.
All of that.
They taught him there very soon.
And there they gave him his job.
And now both of them are doing very well.
Both of them.
And both of them are working there in that place.
Yes.
And he, well, there are boys who didn't go to school because of that.
And they don't have the job that he has now.
And he very soon.
Yes.
And there he is.
And he's making very good money, both of them.
And right now, his car has already been paid.
He's just going to complete his two years of marriage.
He bought a little car of those pretty ones.
A little station.
Yes.
Now he has his... Now he says he already ordered his new pickup.
And he has his house, small, new, his place, all surrounded, all very well arranged, and he is the smallest.
Yes.
All of them have thought, well, well.
Yes.
Yes.
And this, and now this, this girl is just, ah, well, my boy, like right now,
And those are the five boys.
Rudy, well, he lives here.
He got married.
He has his property here.
Then he bought all that property and built his house.
In this town?
In this town.
You're talking about the ones outside?
Yes.
Well, that's all the ones I have outside of here.
Yes.
All these.
Right now, the only ones I have here is this girl.
This one.
Yes.
In the state of Texas.
In the state of Texas, there is Rudy, Reina.
Reina lives here.
Yes.
With her husband.
Yes.
And, Rabiel, Roel, they are here.
And Janie.
Janie, the youngest.
Yes, she is here in the house.
Y el muchacho, mi muchacho el que murió, porque murió uno en un accidente en California.
Él dejó sus tres hijos, que fue el que se le sigue el segundo del mayor.
Y él murió en un accidente.
Allá fue en California, porque él
When I left, he got married, and he stayed here.
He stayed here.
As soon as he got married, I left.
When I was three years old, I came back.
Then I made myself a little house.
Because then I worked very hard for three years.
And I was one of those who pecked the plums, pecked the nuts.
Piscaba, bueno, todo lo que, las corridas que había de las, de las frutas.
Sí.
En California, no todos los años, nomás ciertos años los trabajé.
Nomás una corrida así hasta el día que me vine pa' Texas.
Entonces él, el cincuenta y cinco mismo se fue él a verme.
with his family.
He already had two children, and he went to see me.
So, I was going to be there for the next three years.
So he said, I'm going there.
He said, are you going?
He said, yes.
So we came.
He made this little tree that I have there, to bring us everything.
Y yo, ya se me habían casado el hijo que me acompañaba, ese que está en California.
Entonces, este nos fue a traer, pa' vernos y pa' traernos.
Él se trajo el carro de nosotros con la trela.
Y mi nuera se trajo su carro de ellos con mi muchachito este, Rudy.
And his children, he came with his children and he died.
And then I sent him money to make me that little room because I didn't have anywhere to be.
And he did it.
It was a little room like this.
I came.
And I had surgery here, from my sight, from both eyes, I had surgery.
And it cost me 100 pesos the healing of each eye.
I relieved myself.
In 1956, my boys were here at school.
They had never been here in Texas at school, but that year they were here because I had surgery from the sight.
So they left school, and they just left and we left.
back to California.
So, my son left his wife and children.
And he took them back to California, because at that time, I was the only one who had the eldest daughter.
But she also laughed, but he always wanted to leave some, but with his wife's will.
So,
He was working there with me for a while.
He was doing very well.
He worked.
He wanted to continue his studies.
He followed the school.
The first year he went, he worked with us, with his wife, because he wanted
to go to school.
And the first year that he went to see us went very well, and that was when we came with him.
The second year that he left us, that was in 1956, he was working too.
And he continued his school to compose televisions.
And he put up a fruit shop there on the 9th.
He went, they, he was very Catholic in the mornings, he went very early, it was Sunday, and they went to Mass, he with his children and his wife, because they were both very Catholic.
Very early they went to Mass, and after Mass,
they would go to the shop they had, to sell, because he wanted to continue.
And he was granted.
So, when he left me, he came to work with his family and they came back.
He continued his school and finished it.
And he told me that he was leaving.
So I waited for him.
When he came back, I waited for him.
So I was going to come back that year.
So I told my son, my son, I'm writing to your grandmother.
What do you say?
What do I tell you?
Are you going to go back with us or not?
He says, Mom, I already told my grandma that I'm not going to go back.
I'm going to go until next year.
He says, what I want, you know what, Mom?
You're going to go there.
I want you to come there.
And you go there and bring my grandmother.
And I don't want to go there anymore.
And he says, you know very well that it's always very hard there.
And well, it's hard for one to be there.
Here the jobs are paid better.
Well, then I told my mother.
It's a bad luck that my son was about a month old, I think.
Approximately a month old when this happened.
He made applications, because as he was already known in that mill in Britain, he made applications to work.
He had already fixed his place to put
television work, because there was none in that place.
She says, Mom, I've fixed the place where I'm going to live and where I'm going to put to work.
She says, and then I'm going to put Ruri too, to help me sell.
I said to him, what I don't want is for you to apply as soon as you arrived at the BRIT.
He said, mom, we came to work and maybe it will take a long time to talk to me.
I said to him, it's better that you rest and then apply.

He says, no, he says, well, after all, when they call me, while I'm working, he says, there on the TV, he says, look, I already grabbed three people, I already grabbed what I'm going to buy and everything, I already sold them.
Well, son, I told him, but I didn't want to.
Well, nothing, if they hadn't talked to him late, they talked to him soon.
He said, Mom, they already told me.
I said, what do you mean?
Well, I don't know.
He went to work when they told him.
He was going to a party, I don't know what party, when the mayordomos were going.
Muy a la carrera, porque cada que les dan off, se ponen bien contentos y todo.
Porque cuando mi hijo me escribía las cartas de aquí de Texas, todo el tiempo decía, mamá, voy a tener off tal día, dice.
Voy a descansar.
Ese día, así les dijeron.
Yo andaba trabajando y siempre, siempre, yo todo el tiempo los he encomendado a Dios.
¿Dónde ese día se me pasa a mí?
Tanto que se me pasa decir por Él.
Y me voy yo al trabajo.
I walked about a mile or two away from the town.
Then they say that at lunchtime they were eating, and everyone was eating and talking, because they were going to be off.
And then they ate, and another friend of his
He said, are you leaving?
Yes, he said, I'm leaving.
He said, because I'm looking at you.
He said, no, don't go.
He said, I don't know what they were giving him more than food.
He said, no, he said, I don't want it anymore.
And you know that my boy, all the time, since he started school, he lived all the time in his pocket.
Everything he needed, he brought it there.
All his papers, everything he needed, he brought it there.
Then he left.
The other boy stayed there.
But after a while, he also said that he was leaving.
There were exits outside the mill and there was a lot of loose sand.
The roads had to go to Hacina.
This road from the mill went to Hacina.
And from the end, the trucks had to go to Hacina.
The trucks of the mayordomos came very slow to Hacina.
And this went to Hacina.
A lot of land entered the road.
Where my boy was going to come from, he came from Sina, with a lot of land.
With a lot of land, this friend of his came.
He hit him.
He hit him.
Look at the door.
It jumped.
He was stuck.
A wire got in here.
What was left in his heart?
The shock wire got in here.
He was stuck.
They had to put something in to get him out.
So...
This is a lack of precaution.
Yes.
This truck, they say he had already said, because that was the victim, he was a friend, and he himself killed him.
Yes.
Because they had already said that this truck did not have enough manpower.
